1. Introduction¶

PID controller is a widely used industrial control system. PID stands for "proportional integral derivative". In our project, we are using PID controller to design a trajectory for a vehicle.

The optimization problem we are addressing is that we have a planned trajectory for a vehicle that is at a specific location and speed. This vehicle's speed is controlled by its acceleration, which is in turn contingent on the three parameters of the PID controller, i.e., $k_P$, $k_I$, and $k_D$. Our goal is to find the optimal parameters that lead to the minimal differences between the planned trajectory and the actual trajectory.

Here is our problem:

The planned trajectory starts from location 0 at time 0. The vehicle travels on a $2D$ plane. Its speed at time $t$ is ($sin(t)$, $cos(t)$). The actual location is $(0,1)$ at time 0 and the actual speed is ($28m/s$, $0m/s$) at time 0. Assuming the acceleration cannot be precisely controlled, and always has a random error uniformly distributed over $[−0.2,0.2]m/s$

2. Mathematical model¶

2.A. Variables¶

We have the following decision variables:

  • $0 \le kP_x \le 10$
  • $0 \le kI_x \le 100$
  • $0 \le kD_x \le 1000$
  • $0 \le kP_y \le 10$
  • $0 \le kI_y \le 100$
  • $0 \le kD_y \le 1000$

These three are the key PID controller parameters.

We also have:

  • $T$: the time span
  • $\delta$: time interval
  • $\epsilon$: random error in acceleration control
  • $aP_x$: a vector
  • $aI_x$: a vector
  • $aD_x$: a vector
  • $aP_y$: a vector
  • $aI_y$: a vector
  • $aD_y$: a vector
  • $a_x$: acceleration on x plane at each timestamp, a vector
  • $a_y$: acceleration on y plane at each timestamp, a vector
  • $p_{act_x}$: the position of the actual vehicle on x plane at each timestamp, a vector
  • $p_{act_y}$: the position of the actual vehicle on y plane at each timestamp, a vector
  • $p_{ref_x}$: the position of the planned trajectory on x plane at each timestamp, a vector
  • $p_{ref_y}$: the position of the planned trajectory on y plane at each timestamp, a vector
  • $v_{act_x}$: the velocity of the actual vehile on x plane at each timestamp, a vector
  • $v_{act_y}$: the velocity of the actual vehile on y plane at each timestamp, a vector
  • $v_{ref_x}$: the velocity of the planned trajector on x plane at each timestamp, a vector
  • $v_{ref_y}$: the velocity of the planned trajector on y plane at each timestamp, a vector
  • $int_{act_x}$: the integral of $x$ on x plane at each timestamp, a vector
  • $int_{act_y}$: the integral of $x$ on y plane at each timestamp, a vector
  • $int_{ref_x}$: the integral of $y$ on x plane at each timestamp, a vector
  • $int_{ref_y}$: the integral of $y$ on y plane at each timestamp, a vector

2.B. Constraints¶

A each timestamp $t \ge \delta$, we have the following dynamics, or contraints:

$$a_{P_{t}} = k_{P_{t}} (p_{ref_t} - p_{act_t})$$$$a_{I_{t}} = k_{I_{t}} (int_{ref_{t}} - int_{act_{t}})$$$$a_{D_{t}} = k_{D_{t}} (v_{ref_t} - v_{act_t})$$$$a_t = a_{P_{t}} + a_{I_{t}} + a_{D_{t}} + \epsilon$$$$v_{act_t} = v_{act_{t-\delta}} + \delta \cdot a_{t-\delta}$$$$p_{act_t} = p_{act_{t-\delta}} + 0.5(v_{act_t} + v_{act_{t-\delta}}) \delta$$$$int_{act_{t}} = int_{act_{t-\delta}} + \delta \cdot p_{act_t}$$$$p_{ref_t} = p_{ref_{t-\delta}} + 0.5(v_{ref_t} + v_{ref_{t-\delta}}) \delta$$$$int_{ref_{t}} = int_{ref_{t-\delta}} + \delta \cdot p_{ref_t}$$

2.C. Objective function¶

The objective function is least squares. We want to find the minimum of the sum of the differences between $y$ and $x$. So the objective function is the following:

$$\min \sum^T_{t = 0} (p_{ref_t} - p_{act_t})$$

2.D. Standard form¶

3. Solution¶

First, we import necessary packages:

In [168]:
using Plots, Distributions, Random, JuMP, Ipopt

Based on the problem we have above, we first define the time span and time delta (i.e., the size of each timestamp). Also, we know that the velocity of the planned trajectory is a function of time. To make things easier, we need to have that function ready in the beginning.

In [169]:
# the size of each time stamp is 0.2 second
delta = 0.01

# time span
T = 0.0:delta:10

# Total number of timestamps
N = length(T)

We set the model and declear our variables:

In [170]:
m = Model(Ipopt.Optimizer)

initial_speed = 28
initial_position = 1

# kp, ki, kd
@variable(m, 0 <= Kp_x <= 10)  
@variable(m, 0 <= Ki_x <= 100)  
@variable(m, 0 <= Kd_x <= 1000) 
@variable(m, 0 <= Kp_y <= 10)  
@variable(m, 0 <= Ki_y <= 100)  
@variable(m, 0 <= Kd_y <= 1000) 

# accelertion
@variable(m, ap_x[1:N])
@variable(m, ai_x[1:N])
@variable(m, ad_x[1:N])
@variable(m, a_x[1:N])
@variable(m, ap_y[1:N])
@variable(m, ai_y[1:N])
@variable(m, ad_y[1:N])
@variable(m, a_y[1:N])

# actual car position
@variable(m, p_act_x[1:N])
@variable(m, p_act_y[1:N])
# reference car location
@variable(m, p_ref_x[1:N])
@variable(m, p_ref_y[1:N])

# actual car speed
@variable(m, v_act_x[1:N])
@variable(m, v_act_y[1:N])
# ref car speed
@variable(m, v_ref_x[1:N])
@variable(m, v_ref_y[1:N])

# integral of actual car
@variable(m, int_act_x[1:N])
@variable(m, int_act_y[1:N])
# integral of ref car
@variable(m, int_ref_x[1:N])
@variable(m, int_ref_y[1:N])

Then we have our constraints:

In [171]:
# initial setting at the first timestamp
# ref car position
@constraint(m, p_ref_x[1] == 0)
@constraint(m, p_ref_y[1] == 0)
# ref car int
@constraint(m, int_ref_x[1] == 0)
@constraint(m, int_ref_y[1] == 0)
# ref car v
@constraint(m, v_ref_x[1] == sin(0))
@constraint(m, v_ref_y[1] == cos(0))
# act car position
@constraint(m, p_act_x[1] == 0)
@constraint(m, p_act_y[1] == initial_position)
# act car int
@constraint(m, int_act_x[1] == 0)
@constraint(m, int_act_y[1] == 0)
# act car v
@constraint(m, v_act_x[1] == initial_speed)
@constraint(m, v_act_y[1] == 0)

# # initialize at the first timestamp
@constraint(m, ap_x[1] == Kp_x*(p_ref_x[1]-p_act_x[1]))
@constraint(m, ap_y[1] == Kp_y*(p_ref_y[1]-p_act_y[1]))
@constraint(m, ai_x[1] == Ki_x*(int_ref_x[1]-int_act_x[1]))
@constraint(m, ai_y[1] == Ki_y*(int_ref_y[1]-int_act_y[1]))
@constraint(m, ad_x[1] == Kd_x*(v_ref_x[1]-v_act_x[1]))
@constraint(m, ad_y[1] == Kd_y*(v_ref_y[1]-v_act_y[1]))

# random error in acceleration control
# + rand(Uniform(-0.2, 0.2))
Random.seed!(1234)
@constraint(m, a_x[1] == ap_x[1] + ai_x[1] + ad_x[1] + rand(Uniform(-0.2, 0.2)))
Random.seed!(1234)
@constraint(m, a_y[1] == ap_y[1] + ai_y[1] + ad_y[1] + rand(Uniform(-0.2, 0.2)))

# loop through timestamps:
for i in 2:N
    # act car
    @constraint(m, v_act_x[i] == v_act_x[i-1] + a_x[i-1] * delta)
    @constraint(m, v_act_y[i] == v_act_y[i-1] + a_y[i-1] * delta)
    @constraint(m, p_act_x[i] == p_act_x[i-1] + (v_act_x[i] + v_act_x[i-1])*delta/2)
    @constraint(m, p_act_y[i] == p_act_y[i-1] + (v_act_y[i] + v_act_y[i-1])*delta/2)
    @constraint(m, int_act_x[i] == int_act_x[i-1] + p_act_x[i]* delta)
    @constraint(m, int_act_y[i] == int_act_y[i-1] + p_act_y[i]* delta)
    
    # update y
    t = (i-1)*delta
    @constraint(m, v_ref_x[i] == sin(t))
    @constraint(m, v_ref_y[i] == cos(t))
    @constraint(m, p_ref_x[i] == p_ref_x[i-1] + v_ref_x[i]*delta)
    @constraint(m, p_ref_y[i] == p_ref_y[i-1] + v_ref_y[i]*delta)
    @constraint(m, int_ref_x[i] == int_ref_x[i-1] + p_ref_x[i]*delta)
    @constraint(m, int_ref_y[i] == int_ref_y[i-1] + p_ref_y[i]*delta)
    
    # update ap, ai, ad, and a 
    @constraint(m, ap_x[i] == Kp_x*(p_ref_x[i] - p_act_x[i]))
    @constraint(m, ap_y[i] == Kp_y*(p_ref_y[i] - p_act_y[i]))
    @constraint(m, ai_x[i] == Ki_x*(int_ref_x[i] - int_act_x[i]))
    @constraint(m, ai_y[i] == Ki_y*(int_ref_y[i] - int_act_y[i]))
    @constraint(m, ad_x[i] == Kd_x*(v_ref_x[i] - v_act_x[i]))
    @constraint(m, ad_y[i] == Kd_y*(v_ref_y[i] - v_act_y[i]))
    
    # random error in acceleration control
    Random.seed!(1234)
    @constraint(m, a_x[i] == ap_x[i] + ai_x[i] + ad_x[i] + rand(Uniform(-0.2, 0.2)))
    Random.seed!(1234)
    @constraint(m, a_y[i] == ap_y[i] + ai_y[i] + ad_y[i] + rand(Uniform(-0.2, 0.2)))
end

Our objective function:

In [172]:
# least square
@objective(m, Min, sum( (p_ref_x - p_act_x).^2 + (p_ref_y - p_act_y).^2))

optimize!(m)

5. Conclusion¶

The goal of this project is to find optimal PID controll parameters Kp, Ki, and Kd in order to minimize the sum of squares of the differences between the location of the actual vehicle and the planned trajectory. We constructed the mathematical model based on the problem descriptions and solved it using JuMP (Ipopt solver). The results seem plausible compared to the result based on random parameter setting.

For future directions, we are thinking of extending the problem to higher dimensions. Right now, we assume that vehicles move on a straight line, i.e., move only in one dimension. If the problem is set in 2 dimensions, the dynamics are much more complicated (because we can control both the direction and the volume of the acceleration) but the setting would be more realistic.
